#let images = (
  "7-1": (
    caption: [The structure of two kinds of neurons: (a) A motor neuron with dendrites extending from the cell body, and (b) a sensory neuron with a pseudounipolar structure. Both neurons show the axon extending from the cell body to transmit nerve impulses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-2": (
    caption: [Parts of a neuron showing the dendrites, cell body (soma), nucleus, axon hillock, axon wrapped by Schwann cells forming a myelin sheath, nodes of Ranvier, and the axon terminal. This diagram illustrates the functional regions of a typical neuron.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-3": (
    caption: [The relationship between CNS and PNS. Sensory neurons of the peripheral nervous system carry information into the central nervous system (brain and spinal cord), while motor neurons carry information out. This shows the bidirectional communication between the CNS and peripheral tissues.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-4": (
    caption: [Three different types of neurons based on their structure: Pseudounipolar neurons (sensory) have one process that splits; bipolar neurons (found in retina and cochlea) have two processes; multipolar neurons (motor and association neurons) have multiple dendrites and one axon.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-5": (
    caption: [The different types of neuroglial cells in the central nervous system. Oligodendrocytes form myelin sheaths around CNS axons. Astrocytes have extensions surrounding blood capillaries and neurons. Microglia are phagocytic cells. Ependymal cells line the brain ventricles and central canal of the spinal cord.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-6": (
    caption: [The formation of a myelin sheath around a peripheral axon by a Schwann cell. The myelin sheath is formed by successive wrappings of Schwann cell membranes, leaving most of the Schwann cell cytoplasm outside the myelin. The neurilemma is the outer Schwann cell membrane and cytoplasm.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-7": (
    caption: [An electron micrograph showing unmyelinated and myelinated axons. Myelinated axons have Schwann cell cytoplasm outside their myelin sheath, while Schwann cell cytoplasm also surrounds unmyelinated axons. This demonstrates the structural differences between myelinated and unmyelinated nerve fibers.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-8": (
    caption: [The formation of myelin sheaths in the CNS by an oligodendrocyte. Unlike Schwann cells which myelinate single axons, one oligodendrocyte extends multiple processes like tentacles to form myelin sheaths around several different axons simultaneously.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-9": (
    caption: [The process of peripheral neuron regeneration following axon injury. (a) Initial severing of myelinated axon; (b) distal portion degenerates through phagocytosis; (c-d) the myelin sheath provides a regeneration tube guiding axon regrowth; (e) innervation is restored. This demonstrates the regenerative capacity of peripheral nerves.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-10": (
    caption: [Astrocytes have processes with end-feet that terminate on capillaries and neurons. Astrocyte end-feet take up glucose from blood capillaries and metabolize it to lactate, which serves as an energy substrate for neurons. Astrocytes also take up the neurotransmitter glutamate from synapses and convert it to glutamine (Gln), which is recycled to neurons.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-11": (
    caption: [Observing depolarization and hyperpolarization using recording electrodes. The difference in potential (in millivolts) between an intracellular and extracellular recording electrode is displayed on a computer or oscilloscope screen. The resting membrane potential is approximately -70 mV, with depolarization moving toward 0 mV and hyperpolarization moving more negative.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-12": (
    caption: [A model of a voltage-gated ion channel showing its structure and function. The channel is closed at the resting membrane potential but opens in response to a threshold level of depolarization. This permits the diffusion of specific ions (such as Na+ or K+) through the channel, which is essential for generating action potentials.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-13": (
    caption: [Depolarization of an axon affects Na+ and K+ diffusion in sequence. (1) Na+ gates open and Na+ diffuses into the cell, causing further depolarization in a positive feedback loop. (2) After a brief period, K+ gates open and K+ diffuses out of the cell, repolarizing the membrane in a negative feedback loop that counteracts the initial depolarization.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-14": (
    caption: [Membrane potential changes and ion movements during an action potential. The top graph shows the action potential (blue line) with depolarization rising to approximately +30 mV followed by repolarization. The bottom graph (red lines) shows the net diffusion of Na+ inward during depolarization and K+ outward during repolarization.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-15": (
    caption: [The all-or-none law of action potentials. A single depolarizing stimulus below threshold produces no action potential. Once the stimulus reaches threshold, a full-amplitude action potential is produced regardless of stimulus strength above threshold. This demonstrates the binary nature of action potential generation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-16": (
    caption: [The effect of stimulus strength on action potential frequency. Stimuli of increasing strength that are sustained over time produce increasing frequencies of action potentials. Weak subthreshold stimuli produce no response, while stronger stimuli generate higher frequencies of action potentials, demonstrating how stimulus intensity is encoded.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-17": (
    caption: [Absolute and relative refractory periods during and after an action potential. While a segment of axon is producing an action potential, it is absolutely refractory (cannot respond to any stimulus) during depolarization, then relatively refractory (requires stronger than normal stimulus) during repolarization.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-18": (
    caption: [Cable properties of an axon demonstrating local current flow. When a stimulating electrode injects positive charges producing depolarization at one point, the charges spread to adjacent regions through cable properties. The depolarization decreases with distance due to resistance and capacitance of the axon membrane.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-19": (
    caption: [The conduction of action potentials in an unmyelinated axon. Each action potential injects positive charges that spread to adjacent regions, triggering sequential action potentials. The region that just produced an action potential is refractory and cannot be re-excited, ensuring unidirectional propagation of the nerve impulse.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-20": (
    caption: [The conduction of a nerve impulse in a myelinated axon through saltatory conduction. Because the myelin sheath insulates most of the axon and prevents ion current flow, action potentials are only produced at the nodes of Ranvier (gaps in the myelin). This "leaping" of action potentials from node to node greatly increases conduction velocity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-21": (
    caption: [The structure of gap junctions forming electrical synapses. Gap junctions are water-filled channels (connexons) composed of connexin proteins through which ions can pass directly from one cell to another. This permits electrical impulses to be conducted directly between cells without chemical neurotransmitters.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-22": (
    caption: [An electron micrograph of a chemical synapse between a somatic motor neuron axon and a skeletal muscle cell. The image shows synaptic vesicles clustered at the axon terminal, the narrow synaptic cleft separating pre- and postsynaptic membranes, and the specialized postsynaptic membrane structures.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-23": (
    caption: [The release of neurotransmitter through calcium-triggered exocytosis. Steps show how action potentials open voltage-gated Ca2+ channels, allowing Ca2+ entry. Ca2+ binds to sensor proteins (synaptotagmin), which interact with SNARE proteins holding docked vesicles to the plasma membrane. This triggers fusion of synaptic vesicles with the membrane and release of neurotransmitter into the synaptic cleft.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-24": (
    caption: [The functional specialization of different regions in a multipolar neuron. Integration of synaptic input (EPSPs and IPSPs) occurs in the dendrites and cell body, where ligand-gated channels are located. The axon hillock generates action potentials when threshold is reached. The axon conducts action potentials via voltage-gated channels to the axon terminals.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-25": (
    caption: [Events in excitatory synaptic transmission at a chemical synapse. The postsynaptic neuron has specialized regions: dendrites and cell body contain ligand-gated (chemically-gated) channels, while the axon contains voltage-gated channels. Neurotransmitter binding opens ligand-gated channels causing EPSPs, which can summate to trigger action potentials at the axon hillock.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-26": (
    caption: [Nicotinic acetylcholine (ACh) receptors function as ligand-gated ion channels. (a) The receptor channel is closed until ACh binds to the receptor. (b) Upon ACh binding, the channel opens allowing simultaneous diffusion of Na+ inward and K+ outward. The greater electrochemical gradient for Na+ predominates, resulting in net depolarization producing an excitatory postsynaptic potential (EPSP).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-27": (
    caption: [Muscarinic ACh receptors require G-proteins for signal transduction. Illustrated with cardiac pacemaker cells: ACh binding to muscarinic receptors causes dissociation of G-protein subunits. The beta-gamma complex binds to K+ channels causing them to open. Outward diffusion of K+ results in hyperpolarization, slowing the heart rate.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-28": (
    caption: [The action of acetylcholinesterase (AChE) in terminating synaptic transmission. AChE in the postsynaptic membrane hydrolyzes ACh in the synaptic cleft into acetate and choline. This inactivation prevents continued stimulation of the postsynaptic cell. The acetate and choline are transported back into the presynaptic axon terminal and used to resynthesize acetylcholine.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-29": (
    caption: [The graded nature of excitatory postsynaptic potentials (EPSPs). Stimuli of increasing strength produce increasing amounts of depolarization in a graded manner. When the threshold level of depolarization is reached, action potentials are triggered in the axon. This demonstrates how EPSPs can summate to reach threshold.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-30": (
    caption: [Production, release, reuptake, and inactivation of monoamine neurotransmitters. Monoamines including dopamine, norepinephrine, and serotonin are synthesized in the presynaptic terminal, stored in vesicles, released into the synapse, and then transported back (reuptake) into the presynaptic terminal. Inside the terminal, they are degraded by the enzyme monoamine oxidase (MAO).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-31": (
    caption: [Norepinephrine action through G-protein coupled receptors and second messenger systems. Norepinephrine binding causes G-protein dissociation. The alpha subunit activates adenylate cyclase, which produces cyclic AMP (cAMP) from ATP. cAMP acts as a second messenger to activate protein kinase, which phosphorylates target proteins including ion channels, producing cellular effects.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-32": (
    caption: [GABA receptors containing an integral chloride channel. When GABA (gamma-aminobutyric acid) binds to its receptor, a Cl- channel opens through the receptor protein. This permits inward diffusion of Cl- ions, resulting in hyperpolarization of the postsynaptic membrane and producing an inhibitory postsynaptic potential (IPSP).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-33": (
    caption: [Spatial summation at synapses demonstrating convergence of neural pathways. When only one presynaptic neuron releases excitatory neurotransmitter, the EPSP produced may be insufficient to reach threshold. When two or more presynaptic neurons release neurotransmitter simultaneously, their EPSPs can summate spatially to reach threshold and trigger an action potential in the postsynaptic neuron.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "7-34": (
    caption: [Postsynaptic inhibition through IPSPs. An inhibitory postsynaptic potential (IPSP) makes the inside of the postsynaptic membrane more negative (hyperpolarized) than the resting potential. This increases the amount of depolarization needed to reach threshold, making it more difficult for excitatory inputs to trigger action potentials and thus inhibiting neural activity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7-1": (
    caption: [Terminology pertaining to the nervous system, defining key anatomical and functional terms including neuron, nerve, ganglia, nucleus, tract, somatic motor, autonomic motor, and central/peripheral nervous system structures. This table provides essential vocabulary for understanding nervous system organization.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7-2": (
    caption: [Neuroglial cells and their functions in the central and peripheral nervous systems. Lists cell types including Schwann cells, satellite cells, oligodendrocytes, microglia, astrocytes, and ependymal cells, along with their locations and specific functions in supporting neural tissue.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7-3": (
    caption: [Conduction velocities and functions of mammalian nerves of different diameters. Shows the relationship between nerve fiber diameter (in micrometers), myelin presence, conduction velocity (m/sec), and functional examples. Larger, myelinated fibers conduct impulses faster and serve motor and proprioceptive functions, while smaller unmyelinated fibers conduct slowly and serve pain and autonomic functions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7-4": (
    caption: [Comparison of action potentials and excitatory postsynaptic potentials (EPSPs). Contrasts characteristics including magnitude, duration, amplitude variation, summation ability, refractory period, propagation, and location in the neuron. Action potentials are all-or-none events in axons, while EPSPs are graded potentials in dendrites and cell bodies.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7-5": (
    caption: [Drugs that affect the neural control of skeletal muscles. Lists drugs including botulinum toxin, tetanus toxin, α-bungarotoxin, curare, nerve gas, neostigmine, and saxitoxin, along with their origins and mechanisms of action at neuromuscular junctions. Useful for understanding pharmacological effects on synaptic transmission.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7-6": (
    caption: [Steps in the activation and inactivation of G-proteins in second messenger systems. Outlines the sequence: (1) neurotransmitter binding to receptor, (2) G-protein activation and GTP binding, (3) alpha subunit dissociation and enzyme activation/inhibition, (4) GTP hydrolysis, and (5) G-protein reassociation. Essential for understanding metabotropic receptor signaling.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
